@@eThe Sorcerer Tradition@@N

@@yThe Chromatic Circle@@N
Sorcerers are inheritors of the Chromatic Circle, a pre-academic order of arcanists
who rejected the emerging universities and their narrow specializations. The
Circle's name derives from its founding metaphor: the spectrum of magical schools is
like color, with no single color being the truth of light, and synthesis of multiple
colors the only way to approach full understanding. While the Axiomatic Schools
pressed practitioners toward single-school mastery, the Circle's founders held that
the deepest power lay in synthesis: fire and ice together, healing and destruction
from the same hand.

@@yThe Confluence Texts@@N
The Circle built vast libraries documenting every observed interaction between spell
schools. These Confluence Texts were organized not by individual school but by
interaction type: resonance, interference, amplification, cancellation, and more
complex multi-party effects. The academic mainstream classified much of the content
as unverifiable, not because it was documented incorrectly, but because their
single-school methodology could not reproduce multi-school phenomena. The Circle's
response, that the appropriate answer was to develop multi-school practitioners
rather than declare the phenomena illegitimate, was technically correct and
institutionally ineffective.

@@ySurvival in Apprentice Chains@@N
When the academies absorbed or outlawed most Circle branches, the tradition survived
in small apprentice chains: direct transmission relationships operating outside
institutional frameworks. An apprentice chain has no property to seize, no formal
existence to dissolve, making it substantially harder to destroy than an
institution. Each chain preserved the portions of the Confluence Texts most relevant
to its practitioners' specializations, and some interaction documentation was lost
entirely during the academic consolidation.

@@yBreadth as Weapon@@N
The Sorcerer's combat style brings multiple elemental schools to bear
simultaneously. An opponent who has developed defenses optimized against fire is
poorly prepared for simultaneous water engagement. An opponent whose defenses cover
multiple schools individually is unprepared for the interaction effects that emerge
when those schools are combined. The most dangerous practitioner is not the one who
has mastered one element most deeply but the one who can deploy many in coordinated
interaction.
